CC   -!- FUNCTION: Curlin is the structural subunit of the curli fimbriae.
CC       Curli are coiled surface structures that assemble preferentially
CC       at growth temperatures below 37 degrees Celsius. Curli can bind to
CC       fibronectin.
CC   -!- SUBCELLULAR LOCATION: Fimbrium. Note=Part of the curli surface
CC       structure.
CC   -!- INDUCTION: Under control of the CsgD transcription factor, part of
CC       the csgBAC/ymdA operon. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:17010156}.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: Belongs to the CsgA/CsgB family. {ECO:0000305}.

CC   -!- FUNCTION: Cell-cell signaling protein required for fruiting body
CC       morphogenesis. Necessary for cellular aggregation, for spore
CC       differentiation, and for gene expression that is initiated after 6
CC       hour of starvation. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:2107980,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:2118510}.
CC   -!- SUBCELLULAR LOCATION: Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:2118510}.
CC   -!- DEVELOPMENTAL STAGE: Increases throughout development, reaching
CC       its peak during sporulation. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:1372277}.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: To yeast YKL071W. {ECO:0000305}.

CC   -!- FUNCTION: Curlin is the structural subunit of the curli. Curli are
CC       coiled surface structures that assemble preferentially at growth
CC       temperatures below 37 degrees Celsius. Curli can bind to
CC       fibronectin (By similarity). {ECO:0000250}.
CC   -!- SUBCELLULAR LOCATION: Fimbrium. Note=Part of the curli surface
CC       structure.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: Belongs to the CsgA/CsgB family. {ECO:0000305}.

CC   -!- FUNCTION: Curlin is the structural subunit of the curli. Curli are
CC       coiled surface structures that assemble preferentially at growth
CC       temperatures below 37 degrees Celsius. Curli can bind to
CC       fibronectin. The minor subunit is the nucleation component of
CC       curlin monomers.
CC   -!- SUBCELLULAR LOCATION: Fimbrium. Note=Part of the curli surface
CC       structure.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: Belongs to the CsgA/CsgB family. {ECO:0000305}.

CC   -!- FUNCTION: Plays a role in the extracellular assembly of CsgA into
CC       thin aggregative fimbriae (Tafi) fibers. Assembly may also require
CC       CsgE. Tafi are thought to be assembled via an extracellular
CC       nucleation-precipitation (ENP) pathway, and possibly also via an
CC       intracellular non-CsgC-dependent pathway (By similarity).
CC       {ECO:0000250}.
CC   -!- SUBCELLULAR LOCATION: Periplasm {ECO:0000250}.
CC   -!- INDUCTION: Under control of the CsgD transcription factor, part of
CC       the csgBAC/ymdA operon. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:17010156}.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: Belongs to the CsgC/AgfC family. {ECO:0000305}.

RP   PROTEIN SEQUENCE OF N-TERMINUS, FUNCTION IN THIN AGGREGATIVE FIMBRIAE
RP   ASSEMBLY, SUBCELLULAR LOCATION, DISRUPTION PHENOTYPE, INDUCTION, AND
RP   OPERON STRUCTURE.
RC   STRAIN=27655-3B;
RX   PubMed=17379722; DOI=10.1099/mic.0.2006/000935-0;
RA   Gibson D.L., White A.P., Rajotte C.M., Kay W.W.;
RT   "AgfC and AgfE facilitate extracellular thin aggregative fimbriae
RT   synthesis in Salmonella enteritidis.";
RL   Microbiology 153:1131-1140(2007).
CC   -!- FUNCTION: Plays a role in the extracellular assembly of CsgA (also
CC       known as AgfA, AC P0A1E7) into thin aggregative fimbriae (Tafi)
CC       fibers. Assembly may also require CsgE (AgfE). Tafi are thought to
CC       be assembled via an extracellular nucleation-precipitation (ENP)
CC       pathway, and possibly also via an intracellular non-CsgC-dependent
CC       pathway. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:17379722}.
CC   -!- SUBCELLULAR LOCATION: Periplasm {ECO:0000269|PubMed:17379722}.
CC       Note=Upon overexpression; a small amount is also seen in the
CC       cytoplasm.
CC   -!- INDUCTION: Expressed at low levels in agar-grown cells, part of
CC       the csgBAC (agfBAC) operon. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:17379722}.
CC   -!- DISRUPTION PHENOTYPE: Cells lacking this gene make aberrant thin
CC       aggregative fimbriae (Tafi) which are composed solely of CsgA.
CC       Normal Tafi are composed of CsgA and CsgB at a 20:1 ration.
CC       {ECO:0000269|PubMed:17379722}.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: Belongs to the CsgC/AgfC family. {ECO:0000305}.
